Arrange the wrapped items in the box, with cushion foam or scrunched-up paper placed between each piece. Ensure that the sides of the objects being packed are at least 1" (2.5cm) away from the edge of the box. Certain items require special attention:
For plates, place them on their edge, as they are much stronger packed that way, making certain they do not touch the bottom. Put scrunched up newspaper at the bottom of a box carrying plates, and then slide cardboard, bubble wrap, or foam between them. It is recommended to wrap each plate in a few sheets of paper to keep them well padded and to prevent them from coming into contact with each other. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/a/af/Pack-and-Ship-Your-Fine-China-or-Glassware-Step-4Bullet1.jpg/v4-460px-Pack-and-Ship-Your-Fine-China-or-Glassware-Step-4Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/a/af/Pack-and-Ship-Your-Fine-China-or-Glassware-Step-4Bullet1.jpg/v4-760px-Pack-and-Ship-Your-Fine-China-or-Glassware-Step-4Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":505.27472527472526,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Wrap the lids of items such as sugar bowls, teapots, and casserole dishes separately from the main portion. If the lid is very small, gently tape it in place after wrapping both pieces so it will not be lost. Then wrap the item as a single unit. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/5/56/Pack-and-Ship-Your-Fine-China-or-Glassware-Step-4Bullet2.jpg/v4-460px-Pack-and-Ship-Your-Fine-China-or-Glassware-Step-4Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/5/56/Pack-and-Ship-Your-Fine-China-or-Glassware-Step-4Bullet2.jpg/v4-760px-Pack-and-Ship-Your-Fine-China-or-Glassware-Step-4Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":505.27472527472526,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Make a set of inside spacers from cardboard to keep your glassware separated. Doing this can save them from being broken. Also, heavier glasses should be packed on the bottom, with lighter, more fragile glasses placed on top. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/9/98/Pack-and-Ship-Your-Fine-China-or-Glassware-Step-4Bullet3.jpg/v4-460px-Pack-and-Ship-Your-Fine-China-or-Glassware-Step-4Bullet3.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/9/98/Pack-and-Ship-Your-Fine-China-or-Glassware-Step-4Bullet3.jpg/v4-760px-Pack-and-Ship-Your-Fine-China-or-Glassware-Step-4Bullet3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":505.27472527472526,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
